**Classification**  
**ChestMNIST**:  
The following github repository has a trained classification model and the code that was used to train it on the ChestMNIST dataset: [https://github.com/rsm-13/classifying-chestMNIST](https://github.com/rsm-13/classifying-chestMNIST)  
This repository also has the following research paper linked to it: [https://rsm-13.github.io/radha-m-portfolio/assets/CNN\_chestXray\_final.pdf?](https://rsm-13.github.io/radha-m-portfolio/assets/CNN_chestXray_final.pdf)  
This paper includes a graph of the train loss and validation loss of the model they trained, which is identical to the first graph we documented below.

The first version, or notebook, that we created is **chest\_training\_0.ipynb**. We wrote code that trained a ResNet18 model and recreated results from the research paper so we can improve from that point onwards.   
Train Loss and Validation Loss Results:  
![][image1]  
This notebook trained a model with a peak AUC of 0.77.

The second version, or notebook, that we wrote is **chest\_training\_1.ipynb**. We continued to make improvements in the code related to the divergence in the graph. We then retrained using new code.  
Train Loss and Validation Loss Results:  
![][image2]  
This notebook trained a model with a peak AUC of 0.7814.  
The best model that we were able to obtain for classification comes from our improvements made in our second notebook. The highest AUC reached while training this model was 0.7814. The name of this model is **chest\_best\_model.pth**.

The next step we tried was to test this model on a much smaller subset from the bigger ChestMNIST. Unfortunately, the model was not able to predict any images correctly. 

However, as can be seen in the two links provided below, the highest AUC the authors of MedMNIST were able to get for ResNet18 on ChestMNIST is 0.77. We were able to get an AUC of 0.78.  
[https://www.nature.com/articles/s41597-022-01721-8](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41597-022-01721-8)  
[https://medmnist.com/](https://medmnist.com/)

Even with this small improvement, the model is not able to perform very well. The field of medicine requires precise accuracy as these systems can heavily influence medical situations. This shows that the model cannot be practically used.

The next step is to train a classification model on a different dataset within MedMNIST. One issue with ChestMNIST is that there seems to be almost no difference between images in the dataset, even though there are 14 different labels. By training on a dataset where images look extremely different, our results could be much better.

**PathMNIST**:  
One dataset we can use is PathMNIST. This dataset sets up an impactful problem statement of aiding diagnosis in medical issues. The models being trained can help pathologists detect anal pathology diseases and cancer in the medical workspace.

We start by writing code that will train a ResNet18 model on the PathMNIST dataset. The notebook that we created for this is **path\_training\_0.ipynb**. This notebook uses the dataset where the images are low resolution 28x28 images. The results can be seen inside the notebook. The model reaches a final accuracy of 97.92%.

We then wrote code to train a ResNet18 model on the 224x224 version of the PathMNIST dataset. The notebook that we used to do this is **path\_training\_1.ipynb**. The results can be seen inside the notebook. The final validation accuracy, AUC, and loss are all extremely good numbers. It has a final accuracy of 99.76%.  
The model that this notebook saved is **path\_best\_model.pth**.

We want to use the higher resolution model because we want to generate high resolution images with our generation model. Additionally, highly detailed images allow for better results.

The notebook named **path\_testing.ipynb** tests the trained classification model. The model shows extremely good results.
